The problem is we're calling rotate_right on cb_copy after we've already modified the tree with rotate_left. The tree structure has changed, so cb_copy is no longer in the expected position. A standard AVL deletion algorithm should perform a single rotation operation, not chain two rotations on the same node. After rotating, we need to move up the tree to update parent pointers rather than immediately calling another rotation on the same node.

Looking at how the C implementation handles this, it decrements child counts while traversing upward and performs rotations as needed. The fix is to call rotate_right once and then update our reference to the new root, rather than attempting a second rotation on the same node. Let me examine the C code to understand the traversal pattern better.

