Looking at the code, I can see the bubbling loop starts at line 589. The issue is that we're saving `bu_parent_opt` before rotations happen, but the problem is more fundamental - after a rotation, `bu` may be at a different position in the tree (child of its former child).

Let me look at the C implementation more carefully. In the C code, after `bubble_up->parent_node`, it checks if `bubble_up` is the left or right child of its parent and decrements the count. This happens BEFORE the rotation potentially changes `bubble_up`'s position.

The key insight is: when `bubble_up` is at a position that will change due to rotation, we need to track where it will be AFTER the rotation, not before.

Let me look at the rotation functions to understand what happens. In a right rotation:
- P becomes the right child of L
- L's right child becomes P's left child
- P was at position X (left or right child of its parent)
- After rotation, P is now the right child of L
- L takes P's old position

So after rotation, P's parent changes. And we need to update counts along the path from P's new position upward.

