Interesting! So:
- Before removal: select works correctly, traversal only finds 3 nodes (should be 10)
- After removal: select works correctly (10 values shown, last is None which is correct), traversal only finds 2 nodes (should be 9)

This means the issue is in the traversal (next_node), not in select! The traversal is not finding all nodes. It stops early.

Let me look at the bostree_next_node function:

```rust
pub fn bostree_next_node(node: &Rc<RefCell<BOSNode>>) -> Option<Rc<RefCell<BOSNode>>> {
    let mut current = node.clone();

    if let Some(right) = current.borrow().right_child_node.clone() {
        current = right;
        while let Some(left) = current.borrow().left_child_node.clone() {
            current = left;
        }
        return Some(current);
    }

    loop {
        let parent = current.borrow().parent_node.as_ref().and_then(|w| w.upgrade());
        match parent {
            Some(p) => {
                if p.borrow().right_child_node.as_ref().map_or(false, |r| Rc::ptr_eq(r, &current)) {
                    current = p;
                } else {
                    return Some(p);
                }
            }
            None => return None,
        }
    }
}
```

The traversal stops when there is no right child and when we're coming from the right. But if we traverse to the rightmost node of a subtree, then go to its parent, and that parent has a right child (which it shouldn't, since we found the rightmost), we'd return None...

